RACE.FOOTNOTES: HURRICANE CLAIR clipped heels stumbling at the start, was allowed to settle near the rear five deep down the backside, swooped five wide around rivals beginning at the three eighths marker, loomed the threat turning for home in the five path and was full of run late going away from horses in the final furlong. GET MY DRIFT was alone in the third flight running in the three path down the backside, made little impression three wide on the turn between runners and gave way in mid stretch. SIR SEAMUS had a slim advantage over a few runners down the back straight, set the fast pace on the rail in the turn holding onto a slight advantage, was collared by the winner in upper stretch, never gave in and stubbornly dug in down the lane to win the three horse photo for second money in a tight finish. RED LINE OVERDRIVE settled in midpack five deep down the backstretch, travelled five wide just off the battling foursome through the turn, angled widest in the five path turning for home and finished up closing outside just losing the nod for second at the wire. MAAKWA had a slow start in the beginning, then became headstrong running up behind the pack, had to be steadied nearing the half inside, waited behind the wall of running challenging for the lead on the turn, found a seam in the three path at the eighth pole but was outkicked by a couple foes just missing the nod for the place share. STAR SIGN broke slow to start, was allowed to settle off the quick contesting pace in the early stages, rallied up the inside in the two path straightening out for the drive, lost his path nearing the furlong pole and when clear had late run but by then it was too late. FITZPATRICK stalked near the rear down the backside, was roused three wide midturn, made little headway and could not offer a finish down the lane. HIGHLAND LIFE pressed the issue two wide with multiple runners for the front at the half, continued fighting up top running on the turn, was still in the mix but beginning to fade with rivals on either side at the top of the lane and emptied out at the furlong marker. MR CROWLEY prompted three deep down the backside and through the turn between foes, was the first one in the quartet to give way battling up top midway on the turn and stopped in upper stretch.
